<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Government plays down U-turn on pit
closures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH, DAVID OWEN and MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT was last night putting a brave face on its imminent climbdown
over the future of the coal industry following a cross-party committee's
agreement on plans which would save at least half of the 31 pits threatened
with closure.
As ministers finalised a draft of the white paper on the mining industry, Mr
Tim Eggar, energy minister, denied the government faced a U-turn on the pit
closures.
Pledging to take 'very careful account' of what the committee had to say, Mr
Eggar warned that any proposals were 'likely to cost the economy as a whole
more than the proposals we came forward with in October'.
Ministers have focused on plans by Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, to create an additional market of just 12m tonnes.
But advance warnings yesterday from potential Tory rebels, including Mr
Winston Churchill, chairman of the Conservative Coal Group, suggested the
government would be unlikely to get away with proposals to save fewer than
the 15 or so pits the select committee report implies.
Mr Heseltine is due to meet representatives of Mr Churchill's group in the
next couple of weeks to discuss the government's plans ahead of publication.
One school of thought last night was that the government would risk defeat
in the Commons debate due after its plans are published if it conceded too
little. Labour might win over some Tories by tabling an amendment calling
for the adoption of the select committee's recommendations.
The cabinet body also discussed which pits should make up the total number
to be reprieved, with one line of argument that British Coal should take the
decision on the basis of which pits would be most able to survive when the
support was fully withdrawn.
Other ministers have suggested, however, that the government should decide
and be able to take into account factors such as local unemployment levels,
and the readiness to alter working practices.
The select committee's 300-paragraph report states that there should be no
increase in consumer electricity charges as a result of a proposed five-year
subsidy.
It expresses a strong preference for raising the funds needed by diverting
part of the nuclear levy to coal. As an alternative, the money could be
obtained direct from the Treasury. Ministerial opinion appears to be
hardening against using the nuclear levy as a subsidy route.
This money would help finance the installation of clean coal technology and
subsidise 16m tonnes of extra domestic coal output - enabling British Coal
to deliver it to the electricity supply industry at world prices.
The first-year cost of the report's proposals is estimated at Pounds 300m,
of which the direct coal subsidy would account for about Pounds 120m,
equivalent to Pounds 7.50 a tonne.
The extra market would be created by postponing the planned liberalisation
of the UK electricity market, giving power companies freedom to sign more
long-term contracts.
The report also suggests measures to achieve sales of a further 3m tonnes of
coal outside the electricity sector.
The report proposes both a new licencing authority and an Energy Commission
with powers modelled on the Monopolies and Mergers Commission. It also
recommends that all proposed pit closures be referred to the modified
colliery review procedure.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Coal Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9611  Administration of General Economic Programs.
    P12  Coal Mining.
</IN>
