<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Proposed forces cuts threaten UK's role in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN could not undertake further long-term peacekeeping responsibilities
in Bosnia without a review of the armed forces cuts suggested in the Options
for Change programme, defence officials told MPs yesterday.
The cross-party defence committee was also told the UK had rejected a US
request to send ground troops to Somalia because of the strain the army's
commitments were already causing.
Separately, Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, gave a warning that
Britain's ability to play an active role in seeking to resolve international
conflicts had to be limited.
'Obviously we cannot be everywhere and we cannot do everything,' he said in
a speech at the Royal Institute of International Affairs. Diplomatic
postings were undermanned compared with the UK's main colleagues and
competitors.
He was particularly discouraging about the prospect of a greater role for
the UK in Bosnia. 'To impose and guarantee order in the former Yugoslavia
would take huge forces and huge risks over an indefinite period.'
The defence committee's report, due to be published on February 9, is
expected to call on ministers to rethink the programme of reductions in the
light of the threats to international stability that have emerged since the
end of the Cold War. Labour has renewed its demand for an urgent review of
defence policy.
Mr Bill Reeves, a senior defence official, told the committee the number of
troops needed to enforce the UN peace plan, which proposes breaking up
Bosnia into 10 semi-autonomous provinces, was so large that the decision
would have to be for ministers. One estimate is that more than double the
number of UK troops in place now would have to be sent.
The committee was also told that even in a crisis the army could not send a
second battalion with Warrior armoured vehicles to Bosnia to reinforce the
Cheshire battalion group in the immediate future because troops were tied up
in Northern Ireland.
Hurd hits at US over UN, Page 4
