<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Press watchdog condemns bugging
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Press Complaints Commission, the self-regulatory body for the newspaper
industry, said yesterday that bugging private telephone calls was an
invasion of privacy and therefore contrary to the industry's code of
practice.
But it recognised at its latest monthly meeting that exceptional
circumstances might arise justifying publication. It called for legislation
to clarify the law surrounding the issue.
The commission also deplored publication by some newspapers of a transcript
of a conversation allegedly between the Prince of Wales and Mrs Camilla
Parker-Bowles.
It proposed changes to toughen the existing system of regulation, and agreed
that the composition of the commission should change to include a majority
of lay members to underline the its independence. It also urged editors to
endorse a 'strengthened' code of practice which would be recognised as fair
by the public.
The commission welcomed moves to include copies of the code of practice in
some journalists' contracts.
</TEXT>
