<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Property fraud charges imminent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WEST MIDLANDS police will soon charge with fraud at least 10 and possibly 12
businessmen - including company executives, solicitors and property valuers
 -who allegedly set up a series of illegal commercial property transactions
in Birmingham and the Black Country.
Deals valued at about Pounds 50m have come to light during a nine-month
inquiry by the West Midlands commercial fraud squad, helped by the fraud
investigation group of the Crown Prosecution Service.
The investigation is concentrated on the purchase and sale of 15 properties
where loans of Pounds 6m have been taken out.
Five people have been arrested, though no charges have been brought. Further
arrests are expected in the next two months.
The properties - offices, pubs and warehouses - changed hands as the first
cracks started to appear in the commercial property market during 1989-90,
when credit was still readily available.
The deals allegedly had elements in common, and were made as follows:
A property would be bought legitimately.
It would be given a new, but inflated, professional valuation and sold on
sometimes once, sometimes twice, to companies associated with the original
purchaser.
Loans would be raised on the authority of the inflated valuation. But loans
were not repaid and companies taking them out went into liquidation.
The companies involved were thus able to obtain money at two levels, from
the difference between the original purchase price and the inflated resale
price, and from the loans.
West Midlands police became alerted to the possibility of a commercial
property ring from two sources: first, when they were investigating a series
of residential property mortgage frauds, and second, through concern by the
yet unnamed lending institutions.
It set up an inquiry team of 10 officers, which narrowed its investigation
to specific transactions.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
