<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / International Company News: Norwegian savings bank bounces
back into black
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SPAREBANKEN Nord-Norge, Norway's third-largest savings bank, bounced back
into the black in 1992 with a net profit of NKr160.4m (Dollars 23.9m),
compared with a NKr41.2m loss a year earlier.
The bank said the improvement was due to a reduction in credit losses, lower
costs and improved interest earnings. Credit losses were cut by NKr114.7m to
NKr245m, while net interest income was lifted by NKr17.6m to NKr893.7m.
Credit losses of NKr127m stemming from non-corporate customers were higher
than the board had anticipated, the bank said.
Operating profit, before credit losses, was up by NKr86.9m to NKr405.4m.
Operating costs fell to NKr330.7m last year from NKr385.2m in 1991.
