<PROFILE>_AN-DA1B9AFPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930128
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Technology: Consultant's critique
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN GRUMBALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One message running through all the cases studied so far is that change is
here to stay. In every application of IT to date, the human issues have been
more important than technical ones. Carleton discovered that reluctance to
change can be the sole impediment to a new project.
The company faced a big change in culture when trying to integrate the
drawing office with the production side. The tradition of the job being
complete when the drawings were handed over ended with the introduction of
computer-aided design. Now designers are required to understand the
manufacture of their furniture, as well as its aesthetic qualities.
Change must be managed as a business problem in its own right. Reluctance
can turn into bloody-mindedness if not handled carefully. I think Carleton
did too little preparation for the effects on work practices and paid the
price with an overrun. The Cad system forced greater changes in the
interaction between people than in the way they produce drawings.
While the design of the new system gained consistency from being put
together by just Steve Dodds and a consultant, it suffered from reduced
involvement of the key staff - the line managers. They were involved at the
specification stage, but appeared to have less say in the detailed
implementation. Perhaps more participation throughout the process might have
led to a smoother introduction.
The information technology implementation was not the sole source of
cultural change. The company itself underwent big structural changes as a
result of growth and acquisition. Dodds faces a common problem: maximising
the use of central resources but allowing autonomy in individual divisions.
Despite the problems, the system is now producing tangible benefits for
Carleton. Fast turnaround means being able to serve customers better and
control costs.
The author is a consultant at Software Design and Construction, of Milton
Keynes
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Carleton Furniture Group.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
