FT  28 JAN 93 / Technology: Technology file
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SOFTWARE PRODUCT: Hewlett-Packard's two-dimensional ME-10 computer-aided
design package for 18 seats.  Three-dimensional Solid Modeller is soon to be
introduced.
SOFTWARE SUPPLIER: The ME-10 software was developed, installed and
integrated with other systems by Cad specialist Cadtek, a third-party value
added reseller for Hewlett-Packard.  Cadtek also trained Carleton staff.
HARDWARE: Apollo 9000 Model 700 under Unix for Cad, running 18 seats of the
software, linked to a Unisys 6000/65 under Unix for commercial and
manufacturing systems.
OTHER SYSTEMS: Integrated with the Cad software is the Progress database
which feeds the manufacturing control system and the Unison integrated
financial distribution and manufacturing package from Sam System Services,
running on a separate Unisys Unix computer.  The bill of materials is
transferred directly from the Cad systems to the commercial system for
materials planning.  All four sites use the Cad software, feeding into a
central group file, which then feeds Unison.
SYSTEMS COST: The Cadtek contract amounted to Pounds 250,000, part of an
estimated Pounds 550,000 spent to date on all the systems.  In the Cad
field, software is still cheaper than hardware because Cad needs powerful
and expensive workstations.
