<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Stronger councils watchdog is urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE were bitter clashes in the Commons yesterday over allegations of
corruption in Lambeth borough council, Alison Smith writes.
Some agreement between Labour and Tory MPs that there might be a need for
stronger powers for district auditors and for the Audit Commission, the
independent local government watchdog, was lost in angry exchanges, as Mr
Jack Straw, the shadow environment secretary, faced a concerted attack from
Tories claiming Lambeth exemplified Labour in local government.
While Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary, told MPs the council was
being asked about 'breaches of competition legislation', Mr Straw urged him
to 'condemn the freeloaders, former members of your cabinet, who have had
their hands in the till and their snouts in the trough of privatised
industries'.
Mr Howard told Mr Straw his remarks were 'quite appalling'. Earlier, Labour
had published a dossier of 'mismanagement and fraud' in central government
and Tory local councils.
