<DATE>930128
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Political Notebook: Taxing times
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This week Conservative MPs have been trooping across Whitehall to sip tea
with Mr Norman Lamont and his Treasury colleagues. It is an annual ritual,
ostensibly to give the government's foot soldiers at Westminster a voice in
the shaping of the March Budget.
For much of the past 14 years it has been a sham. During his chancellorship
Lord Lawson frequently disparaged the pleadings of Tory colleagues as
vehemently as those of the Trades Union Congress. Typically his meetings
were held close enough to Budget day to ensure that key decisions had
already been taken.
But this government cannot afford to treat its backbenchers with disdain. It
tried last autumn. It is now about to pay the price in the form of a massive
subsidy to an uneconomic coal industry.
Nor can Mr Lamont. The recovery in his reputation after the Autumn Statement
has proved as short-lived as the false dawns on the economy. This week's cut
in interest rates raised a scarcely audible cheer on the Tory backbenches.
Instead the mood was one of foreboding.
The chancellor's colleagues no longer offer any pretence that they expect
him to remain in the job beyond the summer. Mr Kenneth Clarke and Mr Michael
Howard are front-runners to succeed him. Mr John MacGregor and Mr Michael
Portillo are also in the race.
So Mr Lamont has sent out his invitations early. With one or two exceptions,
the backbenchers are being listened to with studied respect.
As is customary, Mr Lamont has said little himself. The absurdities of
Budget purdah - rigorously enforced by the Sir Terence Burns - dictate that
even the chancellor cannot be trusted not to blurt out a Budget secret. (No
matter that Treasury ministers can chat freely with the same colleagues in
the lobbies of the House of Commons).
Mr Lamont nonetheless has offered clues to his thinking. The conclusion
being drawn by astute Tory MPs is that he remains as uncertain as they about
the best strategy for March 16.
Predictably, his starting point has been to impress on them the awful
medium-term outlook for the borrowing requirement. Mr John Major has said
that the return of economic growth will take care of most of it. Mr Lamont
is not at all convinced.
Just as strikingly, he has been cautious about the pace of economic
recovery: it will be a slow and occasionally faltering. He has intimated
also that it would be dangerous if the economy began to grow strongly when
the rest of Europe remained mired in recession. The Treasury worries more
about the trade gap than it cares to admit.
Mr Lamont has clarified the constraints imposed by the manifesto presented
to the electorate less than a year ago. Mr Major's frequent promise to widen
year-by-year the 20p income tax band is not regarded as a pledge. More
importantly, nor are his parallel reassurances that the Conservatives had no
plans to widen the VAT net.
So the question the chancellor has left in the minds of his guests is not
whether taxes will have to rise, but when and by how much. Only income tax
rates are off-limits. Extension of VAT to newspapers, domestic fuel - a
green tax - and perhaps childrens' clothes are seen as the favourites.
The MPs are no more certain than their host about where the balance should
be struck. A majority are terrified that significant tax increases in March
would lay another frost over those still-elusive green shoots. They have yet
to get used to the prospect of 3m unemployed. But a large minority believe
that unless Mr Lamont makes a start now, the financial markets will take
their revenge.
That brings us to the bright idea being floated in the lobbies: Mr Lamont
should announce a series of tax increases in March but stipulate they will
take effect as part of the December Budget.
The economic logic is that such a strategy would strengthen the recovery by
encouraging consumers to advance spending. It would also reassure the
markets that the government was ready to act over the medium term.
The Treasury traditionally opposes pre-announcement of tax increases for the
good reason that it gives interest groups the opportunity to mobilise
against them.
But for Mr Lamont there may be a political as well as an economic attraction
to make an exception to that rule. If the odds are that he will no longer be
chancellor at the end of the year, why not pre-empt in March the December
Budget?
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311  Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
</TP>
