<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Goalkeeper shoots for the Big Idea
 -Ivo Dawnay talks to Sir Gordon Borrie, head of Labour's social justice
commission
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WITH his brown trilby, neatly furled umbrella and well-fastened mac, Sir
Gordon Borrie might more easily be taken for a spruce version of Tony
Hancock than Labour's latest intellectual eminence grise.
But beneath a modest demeanor lies a Rolls-Royce brain and enough political
surefootedness to enable him to survive as a reform-minded director-general
of the Office of Fair Trading for 16 years - most under the icy glare of Mrs
Thatcher.
Mr Graham Mather, the prominent rightwing policy guru, concedes admiringly
that his deftness at the OFT marked Sir Gordon out as one of the outstanding
public servants of his generation. 'In what must have been literally
hundreds of decisions, he never fumbled the ball once,' he recalls.
Now, in the yet more treacherous world of progressive politics, Sir Gordon's
capacity to keep goal will be tested to the full. Recently appointed
chairman of Mr John Smith's Commission on Social Justice, he has already
impressed his 15 colleagues with an ability to condense crisply lengthy
discussions without reference to a note. That skill will undoubtedly be
needed in the 18 months before he is due to publish his report.
In the sepulchral gloom of parliament's central lobby yesterday, Sir Gordon
made clear that he sees his brief as much broader than merely resolving the
agonised debate over targetted as against universal benefits.
In defining what is meant by social justice, he pledges not to dodge the
pressing question of how to find the resources to provide it. So how will he
re-concile leaping welfare demand with a limited resource base to meet it?
Workfare, perhaps, or some other form of President Bill Clinton's 'tough
love'?
For the moment, he offers no clues beyond displaying a ready scepticism over
cash benefits being the sole club in the government's bag. 'Public money may
be better spent in kind rather than in cash,' he says, listing the provision
of social infrastructure from childcare to crime prevention as essential as
Giro cheques.
The much-cited Pounds 8,000-a-year cost to the exchequer of every unemployed
individual, he says, is a massive underestimate when ramifications of high
joblessness are included such as crime, higher policing bills and insurance
premiums.
The Beveridge report dealt heavily with constructing a social security net.
The Borrie report, acknowledging the funding constraints, intends to tackle
head on the social injustice of long-term unemployment. Surprisingly
perhaps, he also appears undaunted by the broad parameters he has set
himself.
In the first six months, grassroots opinion will supplement his own panel of
experts, garnered in field-trips to Glasgow, Newcastle and Belfast. From
this, Sir Gordon will chisel the outline principles upon which the report
will be based. At this early stage, however, he will not be drawn on whether
its conclusions will be a legislative blueprint or even prescriptive.
Nonetheless, he is aware that for a listless Labour party - desperate for a
Big Idea - a great deal of hope is riding on him at a time when the Tories
too are conducting a parallel tax and benefits review. Indeed, some
mavericks such as Mr Frank Field MP complain that their radical solutions
are getting a fairer hearing with the government than with Labour's front
bench.
Sir Gordon is careful to stress that his commission is fully independent of
Labour, refusing to become enmeshed in the squabbling between the party's
'moderniser' or 'traditionalist' camps. But after a career treading
tightropes between conflicting interest groups, Sir Gordon appears now to be
relishing the opportunity of ruffling feathers. 'I think certainly our
report should cause some upset,' he concludes, fastidiously omitting to
explain whether that 'should' is a mere prediction or, in fact, a goal.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Labour Party (UK).
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651  Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  Personnel News.
</TP>
<XX>
People:-
</XX>
<PE>Sir Borrie, G Chairman Labour Party.
</PE>
