<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / More take holidays in Australia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of British holi-daymakers visiting Australia and New Zealand
trebled in the 1980s as a trend for long-distance holidays grew.
In Europe, the biggest percentage increase was in holidays to Portugal. But
four out of every 10 British people do not take a holiday, a figure which
changed little during the 1970s and 1980s even though 94 per cent of
employees now qualify for more than four weeks paid annual leave.
Watching television remains the most popular home-based leisure activity. In
1991 people watched an average of 26 hours a week. They apparently retained
their critical faculties while doing so; between 1981 and 1991 complaints
about television advertising more than doubled.
Although the development of satellite, cable and video has extended the
range of television available, there has been a slight decline in the time
spent viewing since 1986.
Listening to radio, by contrast, increased from an average of less than nine
hours a week in 1986 to nearly 10 1/2 hours in 1991.
People aged 16 to 34 were keenest, with an average of nearly 13 hours.
Blackpool pleasure beach retains its position as Britain's most popular
tourist attraction with free admission - 6.5m visitors were counted there in
1991 - followed by the British Museum with 5.1m.
If this year's Social Trends suggests that the glories of Mammon may have
faded a little for many British people, there is no evidence that they are
seeking solace in the eternal.
Adult membership of the main Christian churches fell by one-sixth to less
than 7m between 1975 and 1990, although Muslim, Sikh and Hindu worshippers
all increased.
</TEXT>
