<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Campaigners go to work on smoking: Legal action will lead to
more bans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR Midland Bank's 45,000 UK employees, a smoke-free working environment has
been a fact of life since May last year. The bank, like an estimated 20 per
cent of employers, forbids staff and public to smoke on its premises.
The case of Ms Veronica Bland, awarded Pounds 15,000 in an out-of-court
settlement for the alleged ill-effects of passive smoking, illustrates why
Midland and many other organisations no longer wish to risk exposing workers
to cigarette smoke.
Indeed, Ms Bland's employer, Stockport Borough Council, has itself
introduced a no-smoking policy - implemented, it pointed out yesterday, six
months before she started her legal action. Other organisations which ban
smoking include Marks and Spencer, IBM and the Inland Revenue.
The move in the UK away from smoking in public places and at work is in line
with developments elsewhere in Europe, and in the US and Australia. The
latter, in particular, presents close parallels with developments in the UK,
says the pressure group Action on Smoking and Health (Ash).
The case in 1989 of Mr Sean Carroll, a Melbourne bus driver, produced an
overnight change in employers' attitudes, according to Ash. Before he died
of cancer Mr Carroll won a Pounds 32,000 out-of-court settlement for the
alleged effects of passive smoking. Almost immediately, states began to
legislate against smoking in public places and at work.
Even in France, where Gauloises are practically a national emblem, smoking
has been severely restricted in public places and open-plan offices.
In the US federal regulations are imminent which will force companies with
more than 10 workers to ban smoking. The move follows the Environmental
Protection Agency's classification of the smoke breathed out by smokers as a
significant carcinogen to those around them. The agency attributes about
3,000 lung-cancer deaths a year to passive smoking.
UK experts take a slightly lower-key approach. In 1988 a government advisory
body, the Independent Scientific Committee on Smoking and Health, reviewed
all the evidence and concluded that passive smoking caused a small increase
in the risk of lung cancer. Even so, it added, several hundred lung cancer
deaths a year in the UK might be attributable to passive smoking.
How much compulsion UK companies should face remains an open question. The
Confederation of British Industry is adamant that individual employers
should be left to assess the risk of passive smoking.
The same line has, until now, been taken by the government, but this may
change. Dr Brian Mawhinney, the health minister, has warned recently that
the government would not rule out legislation if voluntary bans failed to
work.
Back at Midland Bank, the need for flexibility and compassion towards
addicts is recognised. 'If a customer has a problem with his business and
comes in to see the manager, he might feel he needs a cigarette,' the bank
said. 'You have to have some element of common sense about whether you would
stop him.'
</TEXT>
