<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / BNFL faces safety charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH NUCLEAR Fuels is to be prosecuted for four alleged breaches of site
licence conditions at its Sellafield reprocessing works in Cumbria, the
Health and Safety Executive said yesterday.
The prosecution follows investigations by the HSE's Nuclear Installations
Inspectorate into an incident during routine testing work last April at the
Windscale Vitrification Product Store, part of a Pounds 240m complex opened
in February 1991.
The inspectorate alleges:
An unauthorised modification had been carried out, disabling gamma monitor
interlocks (radiation detectors) designed to ensure safety.
Operations were done for which there were no adequate written instructions.
The interlocks were not properly connected.
There were not adequate arrangements for testing the interlocks associated
with the product flask.
The HSE said that while there were no radiological consequences from the
alleged events, it was prosecuting because of the importance it attaches to
compliance with licence conditions. BNFL will appear before Whitehaven
magistrates on February 26.
</TEXT>
