<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Boiler shutdown 'led to Braer disaster'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BOILER shutdown on the tanker Braer for 'routine adjustment' led to the
ship breaking down and going aground in violent seas in the Shetland islands
earlier this month.
In his first detailed public statement on the disaster, Mr Michael Hudner,
chief executive of B + H Ship Management, the US operators of the
Liberian-registered vessel, defends the competence of the tanker's Greek
captain and his largely Filipino crew. The ship had been passed as sound in
a number of outside inspections.
He also defends the choice of route taking the Braer through the 25 mile
channel between Shetland and Fair Isle on its voyage from Norway to Canada.
Other routes were 'less attractive from the standpoint of safety and
navigation'.
Mr Hudner says the boiler, shut down before midnight on January 4, more than
12 hours before the stranding at 11.20am on January 5, could not be
re-ignited and therefore ceased to warm the heavy fuel oil used in the main
engine. This made a switch to diesel oil necessary just after midnight.
Although the diesel oil used by the main engine was automatically purified,
the diesel required to fuel the boiler and power the ship's generators was
found to be contaminated with seawater. This had apparently entered through
the diesel tank's air vents, which may have been damaged by some steel pipes
being carried on board, Mr Hudner says.
After further efforts to remove the water and re-ignite the boiler failed,
the master decided to seek shelter and at 4.36am the Braer, now 10 miles
south of Sumburgh Head, changed course for the Moray Firth. The ship then
lost propulsion from the main engine and a few minutes later the generators
failed, blacking out the ship except for emergency lighting.
He says the Braer contacted the coastguard at about 5am but did not request
the assistance of a tug, the master calculating that it would slowly drift
clear of land. Coastguards located the tug Star Sirius at Lerwick in
Shetland at 6.04am, however, and the tug left harbour at 7.10am.
In the meantime the captain was advised by the RAF and the coastguards to
allow the evacuation of the crew by helicopter because the ship was in
danger of going aground and causing an explosion. The evacuation took place
between 8.25am and 8.50am and the tug arrived on the scene at 9.45am.
An attempt at 10.30am to save the ship - with five men landed from a
helicopter - failed. The Braer, with a cargo of 85,000 tonnes of crude, went
aground at Garth's Ness at 11.20am, Mr Hudner says.
</TEXT>
