<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Prior says rail plans could destroy jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD PRIOR, the former Tory cabinet minister who chairs General Electric
Company, yesterday warned that the government's rail privatisation plans
could destroy Britain's trainmaking industry over the next three years.
His warning came as the government tried to meet the industry's concerns by
publishing a consultation paper on its plans to encourage trainmaking after
privatisation.
GEC is one of Britain's biggest railway equipment manufacturers, employing a
workforce of 4,000 on trainmaking and signalling in a sector directly
employing more than 12,000.
Lord Prior told the Commons transport committee that the industry had little
work beyond the completion of existing contracts and that there were very
few home orders in sight.
He feared that the government's rail privatisation plans would lead to a
drying up of orders because the transition to the new regime would be
accompanied by a hiatus in investment. The result would be heavy
redundancies.
'Unless some orders come in reasonably quickly there will be no rolling
stock industry left in three years' time,' Lord Prior said. 'I don't think
that's an exaggeration.'
Lord Prior's warning echoed the Railway Industry Association's claim last
month that train manufacturers were 'staring annihilation in the face'
because of the government's plans.
Trainmakers fear that companies winning franchises to operate BR's passenger
services will be reluctant to buy or lease new rolling stock because of the
risk that they will be unable to find a buyer for it should they fail to
renew their franchises.
Mr Roger Freeman, minister for public transport, yesterday sought to allay
the industry's fears about an investment famine with assurances that the gap
would be bridged.
He said British Rail had been given permission in the 1992 Autumn Statement
to lease Pounds 150m-worth of trains. Beyond that, BR would still be
operating non-franchised services for years to come and would continue
ordering new trains.
In addition, he hoped private-sector train manufacturers would embark on the
speculative building of rolling stock which it would then lease to train
operators. The government also planned to establish public-sector train
leasing companies which would be privatised as quickly as possible.
Addressing doubts about the private sector's willingness to invest in new
trains, Mr Freeman said he did not rule out the possibility of making some
franchises conditional on such investment.
Railway Privatisation: Passenger Rolling Stock. Passenger Services Division,
Department of Transport, 2 Marsham Street, London SW1P 3EB.
</TEXT>
