<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Consultation paper on rail privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Transport's consultation paper on rail privatisation and
passenger rolling stock envisages a time of healthy leasing in new and
second-hand trains.
There is one big problem: operators will be reluctant to take out a 15-year
lease on a train if their franchise expires after five years.
A four-pronged transitional arrangement is proposed to overcome this:
Companies might win franchises for longer than five years if they promise to
re-equip a line with new trains.
The franchising authority might agree that if a franchisee investing in new
trains failed to win renewal the successor would be required to take over
the trains.
The government might be prepared to underwrite a proportion of the losses
suffered by a train lessor who failed to find a buyer or lessee for trains
made redundant by the loss of a franchise.
Public sector train leasing companies might be set up as interim measure,
though the government would aim to privatise them soon.
</TEXT>
