<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / HK political boundary plans get first airing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HONG KONG Governor Chris Patten's plans for the territory's political
development will receive their first airing tomorrow when the colonial
government publishes legislation for the creation of an electoral boundaries
commission.
The commission, regarded as one of the government's less controversial
proposals, will have three members, one a High Court judge who will act as
chairman.
It will make recommendations to the governor's Executive Council on the
boundaries of 20 one-member constituencies in the Legislative Council, Hong
Kong's law-making body, for the 1995 elections. These members will be
returned by universal suffrage. The commission will be responsible for the
conduct of the elections. The impartiality of Hong Kong's electoral system
will be strengthened by the commission, an official said.
