<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Krajina's Serbs demand Croat withdrawal within 24 hours
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SERBS in Krajina, the disputed Serb enclave in Croatia, yesterday demanded
that Croatian forces withdraw within 24 hours from territory seized during
their six-day offensive.
The ultimatum was issued as the fighting took a new twist, with Serb forces
launching a counter-offensive. They later claimed to have seized strategic
villages around the Maslenica bridge, which joins central Croatia with its
southern Adriatic coast and which was the initial objective of the Croatian
forces.
In addition, the United Nations Protection Force disclosed last night 21 of
its number had been detained by the Serb rebels since Sunday in a hotel in
Benkovac, a Krajina town which has come under fire from Croatian troops.
Ms Shannon Boyd, an Unprofor official, said in the Croatian capital Zagreb:
'The Serb militias say the UN police have been restricted for their own
security. But this is totally unacceptable. There is no legitimate reason
for this.'
In New York, Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary-general, last night
accused the Croats of widening attacks against UN-monitored areas and said
these had jeopardised the entire peace process in the region.
Briefing the Security Council, he said Croatian troops were shelling new
targets and that their offensive had 'serious implications' for the future
of the 16,000 UN peace-keepers in Croatia, whose mandate comes up for
renewal in about three weeks.
The commander of UN forces in the former Yugoslavia, General Satish Nambiar,
yesterday met Serb leaders at Knin, the capital of Krajina. Mr Boro
Martinovic, a minister in the self-styled Krajina government, said: 'We told
him the Croats must withdraw beyond the ceasefire line by noon on Wednesday.
If not, we will have no choice but to clean the terrain by ourselves.'
Following the Security Council condemnation of the Croat offensive across UN
lines, President Franjo Tudjman of Croatia on Tuesday said he would only
order the withdrawal of Croat forces if the Serb militia returned their
heavy weapons to UN control. But hopes of a ceasefire yesterday faded amid
the Serbian counter-offensive.
In Geneva, where Lord Owen and Mr Cyrus Vance are co-chairing peace talks on
the conflict in Bosnia-Hercegovina, Mr Alija Izetbegovic, Moslem president
of Bosnia, yesterday threatened to abandon the talks. He cited continued
Serbian attacks on Moslems as the reason for the threat.
Mr Izetbegovic and Mr Mate Boban, Bosnia's Croat leader, announced a
cessation of hostilities between Croat and Moslem troops in Bosnia and vowed
to resurrect their alliance against the Serbs. But the International Red
Cross said intensified clashes between Croats and mainly Moslem Bosnian
forces around Busovaca, central Bosnia, had blocked the main humanitarian
aid routes into Bosnia.
Meanwhile, a British naval task force headed by the aircraft carrier Ark
Royal is now in position in the Adriatic.
The task force is carrying reinforcements for the 2,400 British troops
helping to protect UN aid convoys in Bosnia.
</TEXT>
