<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Sterling fall puts renewed pressure on punt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING came under renewed selling pressure against the D-Mark and the
dollar yesterday as the government's 1 percentage point cut in base rates
continued to undermine the confidence of investors in the British currency.
The pound fell more than 4 pfennigs in intra-day trading, bottoming out at
DM2.388, amid strong selling from bank dealers, overseas companies and
institutional investors.
The base rate cut from 7 per cent to 6 per cent and sterling's subsequent
fall triggered fresh tensions in the European exchange rate mechanism,
pushing the punt below its floor against two ERM currencies.
There was a strong belief in the foreign exchange market that sterling's
fall had left the punt heavily overvalued against the pound, undermining
Ireland's trading position with the UK.
Ireland's central bank once again responded to the speculative attack on its
currency by raising its overnight lending rate to 100 per cent, only two
days after it had reduced the rate by one percentage point to 14 per cent.
On the Dublin interbank market, one month interest rates doubled to around
35 per cent.
The moves failed to lift the punt above its floors against the Belgian franc
and Dutch guilder after official ERM trading closed at 4 pm in London.
Sterling closed in London at DM2.3975, down nearly 3 pfennigs on the day,
and more than 11 pfennigs below the level at which it was trading three
weeks ago. Against the dollar, it closed down nearly 2 1/2 cents at Dollars
1.538. In New York it closed at DM2.3965 and at Dollars 1.5105.
There was a more modest deterioration in sterling's trade weighted index,
which measures the pound against a basket of currencies and which Mr Norman
Lamont, the chancellor, has said he monitors closely. The index fell from
78.9 to 78.6.
The values of sterling and the punt were undermined by a growing perception
in markets that the Bundesbank may ease its short-term rates more slowly
than had been anticipated earlier this year.
Mr Lothar Muller, a member of the Bundesbank council, said conditions were
not right for another cut in German interest rates.
Uncertainty about the direction of German rates also undermined the lira,
which in London fell sharply against the D-Mark from L919.75 to L933. In
late New York dealing it was trading around L936 against the D-Mark.
The Irish government said it was determined to continue defending the punt.
However, the renewed pressure after more than a week of an easing of
tensions within the ERM is rapidly eroding the political consensus the
government had succeeded in creating last September in defending the
currency.
The Irish Farmers' Association is to hold an emergency meeting of its
national executive on Monday to discuss the crisis, which it says has badly
affected Irish food exports into the UK market.
German bankers back tough interest rate line, Page 2
Lex, Page 22
Currencies, Page 35
Irish stock market, Page 41
</TEXT>
