<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Council employee wins Pounds 15,000 over passive smoking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A COUNCIL employee has won Pounds 15,000 compensation for the alleged
effects of passive smoking at work, in what is believed to be the first such
case in the UK.
As an out of court settlement, the case does not set a legal precedent, but
Action on Smoking and Health, the anti-smoking campaign, said there would be
a flood of similar claims from passive smoking victims.
Nalgo, the white-collar local government union, which backed the worker's
case, said the award should be 'a warning shot across the bows to all
employers who ignore the risks of smoking to non-smokers'.
Dr Brian Mawhinney, health minister, yesterday reiterated that the
government would consider legislation to outlaw smoking in public places and
at work if voluntary bans did not succeed.
The government's aim is for 80 per cent of public places to be smoke-free by
1994, with smoking banned for most employees by the year after.
Ms Veronica Bland, a 36-year-old non-smoker, who still works for Stockport
Metropolitan Borough Council, claims that between July 1988 and September
1989 she worked close to seven employees who smoked continually. She
estimates that she inhaled smoke from at least 150 cigarettes each working
day.
Ms Bland developed chronic bronchitis and alleges that, until the council
introduced a no-smoking policy in 1990, she suffered from persistent coughs,
sore throats, catarrh and eye irritations. She also says her singing voice -
she is a member of a choir - has deteriorated.
Stockport said yesterday that the settlement of Ms Bland's claim by the
council's insurers was made without any admission of liability. It added
that the council was one of the first local authorities in the country to
implement a scheme which establishes employees' right to work in smoke-free
offices.
The Association of British Insurers said the settlement was 'in no way a
precedent'. There was nothing legally or morally binding about it and there
would be 'no softening of the position of the insurance industry in fighting
this sort of case'.
Stockport's insurers had decided it was less costly to settle with Ms Bland
than investigate and pursue the case in court, said the ABI. The industry
was still waiting for a suitable test case.
Mr John Cridland, Confederation of British Industry director of
environmental affairs, said Ms Bland's case would 'certainly strengthen the
trend' towards smoke-free working environments. However, he said he did not
think the award was a 'huge step in itself' because it was a voluntary
out-of-court settlement.
Emphasising that the CBI did not favour a legal obligation for employers to
ban smoking, Mr Cridland added that 'many employers, certainly those who
care, as most do, about having a healthy and motivated workforce, are
already well down the road to voluntary policies'.
Drawing attention, Page 6
Tobacco advertising bill, Page 8
</TEXT>
