<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Government Bonds: UK gilt prices mixed after Bank auction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UK government bond prices were mixed in the wake of the Bank of England's
Pounds 2.5bn auction of 8 1/2 per cent Treasury stock. Dealers said that
although the market was long of stock at current levels, prospects had
improved now that the auction was out of the way.
Cover on the auction was 1.18 times, the lowest since the Bank resumed its
auctions in April 1991, but above the all-time low of 1.07 times reached in
January 1988. The 'tail' was also long at  7/32 , which compared with just
1/32 or  1/16 in previous auctions.
After the auction, the Bank of England issued a further Pounds 550m worth of
existing gilts: Pounds 300m of 8 per cent gilts due 2003 at 124 7/16 ;
Pounds 100m of 2 1/2 per cent index-linked gilts due 2001 at 162; and Pounds
150m of 2 1/2 per cent index-linked gilts due 2009 at 147 1/8 .
The Liffe March long gilt futures contract fell to 100.26 immediately after
the auction results but then climbed to the day's high of 101.09. It closed
at 101.03, down  1/16 on the day on volume of 55,937 lots.
GERMAN government bond prices got some support from the successful auction
of 7 1/8 per cent 10-year bonds for the Treuhand privatisation agency which
raised DM4.76bn.
However, dealers said the shorter end of the market underperformed the
longer end as remarks by Mr Helmut Schlesinger, Bundesbank's president, on
Tuesday dashed hopes of an early cut in domestic interest rates.
The Liffe March bund futures ended 0.12 point higher at 92.83 in average
volume of 42,770 lots. Dealers who are expecting a downward correction in
the market said the contract could fall to around 92.30.
FRENCH government bond prices also came under pressure at the short end as
rate cut hopes faded in spite of a firm franc. The market was weighed down
by news that Standard &amp; Poors, the US credit rating agency, may downgrade
the credit rating of six French banks.
The 8 1/2 per cent OAT due 2003 ended down 0.19 point at 103.80 to yield
7.95 per cent, while on the Matif, the March bond futures contract closed at
112.92, down 0.14 on the day in volume of 125,662 lots.
US TREASURIES rose across the maturity range after strong demand at the
afternoon sale of new five-year notes erased the market's bad memories of
Tuesday's much less successful two-year note auction.
In late trading, the benchmark 30-year government bond was up  5/32 at 104
19/32 , yielding 7.240 per cent. At the short end of the market, the
two-year note was even firmer, up  3/16 at 99 31/32 , yielding 4.250 per
cent.
The lack of demand for the two-year notes on Tuesday caught dealers and
investors by surprise, and cast a cloud over the auction of Dollars 11.5bn
in five-year notes scheduled for the afternoon. Early indications that
demand for the five-year issue would be strong, however, helped buoy prices
in morning trading.
Strong demand for the new issue resulted in the five-year notes being
awarded at a yield of 5.66 per cent, better than expected.
Prices were also helped by comments from Mr Alan Greenspan, the chairman of
the Federal Reserve, who said that while the economy was growing at a
quicker pace, it was still moving into 'headwinds'.
</TEXT>
