<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Investor interest low at Pounds 2.5bn gilt auction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT could face difficulty in funding its heavy public sector
borrowing requirement next year following a poor response to yesterday's big
auction of gilt-edged stock.
Investor interest in the Bank of England's Pounds 2.5bn gilts auction was
the lowest for five years and there were signs that the central bank
accepted bids at a discount to the market price to be sure of selling the
full amount on offer.
However, the Bank said it was satisfied with the outcome of the auction of 8
1/2 per cent Treasury stock due 2007, and later issued three further
tranches of existing gilts worth Pounds 550m.
The low interest could partly be explained by muted demand from marketmakers
in the gilt-edged market, who were still smarting from Tuesday's unexpected
cut in the base rate.
Many, who had gone short of stock in anticipation of the auction, had to buy
back stock at higher prices after the one point cut in the base rate
prompted a sharp rise in gilts prices.
Mr John Shepperd, economist at SG Warburg, said yesterday's response to the
auction implied that the government may have created difficulties for itself
as a result of the timing of the base rate cut. 'The timing reduced the
gilt-edged marketmakers' confidence in the whole process of auctions, which
have been the backbone of the funding system recently,' he said.
The cover, or the amount by which demand exceeds supply, on the auction was
1.18 times, the lowest cover since the Bank of England resumed its auctions
in April 1991, but above the lowest-ever 1.07 times recorded in January
1988.
Another indication that the auction had not been a resounding success was a
much longer 'tail' - the difference between the average accepted price and
the lowest accepted price - of   7/32 . This compares with tails of just
1/32 or  1/16 in previous auctions.
'If you are allowing some investors to take the stock at such a discount,
then you are really very keen to get the stock away,' said Mr Michael Burke,
an economist at Yamaichi.
Economists believe the government is about fully-funded for the current
fiscal year following yesterday's auction, and that any surplus will be put
towards the 1993-94 requirement which they estimate at Pounds 55bn.
Lex, Page 22
Details, Page 30.
</TEXT>
