<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 93 / Greenspan sees 'hopeful signs of solid growth' in US economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR ALAN GREENSPAN, the Federal Reserve chairman, yesterday said the pace of
US economic growth was becoming firmer, and signalled that he would
co-operate with the Clinton administration in promoting a sustainable
recovery.
The Fed saw more hopeful signs of a solid recovery and would 'continue
playing a constructive role' in supporting growth, he said under questioning
from congressional Democrats.
However, while appearing to rule out any tightening of monetary policy in
the foreseeable future, he gave no indication that the Fed would cut
interest rates further in response to a White House deficit reduction plan.
President Bill Clinton said yesterday he was unsure whether he could meet
his goal of cutting the deficit by Dollars 145bn (Pounds 95bn) within four
years without having to raise taxes.
He would lay out an economic plan in his State of the Union address on
February 17.
Mr Greenspan said activity had been increasing at a 'firmer pace of late'.
The head winds that had retarded growth had slackened somewhat, but 'this is
not to say that we have clear sailing ahead'.
Households and businesses were still 'struggling to redress structural
imbalances unparalleled in the postwar period' and slow growth abroad was
acting as a drag on exports and output.
Job growth had been abnormally slow because of structural changes in the US
economy, including a 'dramatic improvement in productivity' since early
1991. Much of this reflected efficiency gains following heavy investment in
new computer technology.
While this augured well for long-run growth and international
competitiveness, it implied 'continuing adjustments in the workforce'.
Mr Greenspan was testifying before the Joint Economic Committee of Congress,
his first appearance on Capitol Hill since Mr Clinton's election victory.
Democrats on the committee criticised him for cutting interest rates too
slowly and demanded that he support fully White House and congressional
efforts to revive the economy.
Mr Greenspan said co-operation was 'accelerating' between the Fed and the
administration. The traditional weekly breakfast meeting between the Fed
chairman and the Treasury secretary had been reinstated after a lapse during
the Bush years. Mr George Stephanopoulos, the White House spokesman,
confirmed that the Fed and the White House were trying to co-operate more
fully. He said Mr Clinton and Mr Greenspan 'share the same goals', which
included a recognition of the need for more jobs.
Mr Greenspan expressed support for tough and credible action to reduce the
budget deficit. There was no risk of the economy being weakened by too
ambitious a package of cuts. If long-term interest rates were to fall,
specific actions affecting spending and revenue totals had to be agreed.
However, Mr Greenspan refused to promise lower interest rates in response to
a tightening of fiscal policy. He said low inflation was a 'precondition'
for sustainable growth. The US had to avoid the 'stop-go' cycles of the
past.
Bonds Page 30
US stocks Page 41
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  USA.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311  Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P91  Executive, Legislative and General Government.
