<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Akers to quit as IBM's chief executive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS Machines, the troubled US computer group, said
yesterday Mr John Akers would step down as chief executive. The company also
said its quarterly dividend would be slashed from Dollars 1.21 to 54 cents,
the first time it has cut its payout to shareholders.
In an unprecedented move, IBM said the search for a new chief executive
would be conducted outside the company as well as within the ranks of its
senior executives.
The management shake-up and dividend cut reflect the severity of IBM's
difficulties and rising pressure from shareholders. Last week, it reported a
net loss for 1992 of Dollars 4.9bn (Pounds 3.2bn) on sales of Dollars 64bn,
the largest annual loss in US history, after taking restructuring charges of
Dollars 11.6bn to cover the cost of drastic cuts in manufacturing and 40,000
job losses.
Wall Street reacted positively to IBM's announcement, but analysts said the
long-term health of the company remained in question. They expect additional
large-scale write-offs. The share price, which has fallen more than Dollars
100 since July, surged yesterday to almost Dollars 53 when trading opened,
but ended at Dollars 49 1/8 .
The management changes were widely seen as a signal that IBM was prepared to
take radical measures to return the company to profitability as quickly as
possible. The dividend cut, although a disappointment to shareholders, had
been expected after last week's earnings announcement.
Mr Akers, who is 58 and had been expected to retire at the end of 1994,
proposed at a meeting of IBM's board in New York on Monday that a search for
a replacement be accelerated, IBM said.
'It is the right time in IBM's business transformation to identify new
leadership,' Mr Akers said in a statement. He will remain chairman, at least
for the time being. Underscoring the dramatic cultural changes that have
shaken IBM under Mr Akers, he is the first chief executive of the company to
retire early and the first for whom the board may seek an outside
replacement.
Moreover, IBM's non-executive directors have gained considerable power over
IBM's executives in recent days. It was not immediately clear if they forced
Mr Akers' resignation, as their counterparts recently did with the General
Motors and American Express chief executives.
Mr Akers has clearly been under increasing pressure from institutional
investors and has been heavily criticised by industry commentators. It was
also apparent that IBM's board wanted to prevent a prolonged controversy
over the leadership.
The selection of a new chief executive will be made by a new committee of
outside directors chaired by Mr James Burke, former chairman of Johnson and
Johnson and a long-time IBM board member. In the past such appointments have
been made by executive directors.
In other top management changes, Mr Frank Metz Jr, IBM's chief financial
officer, who is 59, will retire a year earlier than expected. He will be
succeeded by Mr Paul Rizzo, a former IBM vice-chairman. Mr Jack Kuehler, 60,
will relinquish the title of IBM president, and becomes a board
vice-chairman.
Lex, Page 20 Departure marks desperate battle for change, Page 21 US stocks,
Page 39
