<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Brown joins Scottish pressure for
Rosyth inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR GORDON BROWN, the shadow chancellor, joined Scottish industrial lobbyists
yesterday in urging an inquiry into allegations of Ministry of Defence bias
against the Rosyth naval dockyard in favour of Devonport.
His demand follows reports that the Scottish yard was poorly advised by the
MoD on refurbishment so as to prejudice its chances in a crucial battle with
Devonport over warship and nuclear sub-marine refitting contracts.
With a decision on the contracts imminent, campaigners for Rosyth -
Scotland's largest single employer - are lobbying parliament today prior to
a series of protests and demonstrations in Scotland. They say that failure
to win the submarine contract would cost the Scottish economy 18,000 jobs
and up to Pounds 10bn.
Yesterday, Mr Brown demanded an inquiry into the bias allegations within the
MoD alongside independent investigations by the defence and Scottish select
committees of the Commons.
Labour MPs are also questioning the links between Mr George Allin, a leading
MoD civil servant in charge of the refitting department, and Brown and Root,
the US engineering company that holds a 30 per cent stake in Devonport's
management company.
The MoD has pointed out that while Mr Allin worked on secondment for the US
company, he had also worked at the Rosyth dockyard for three years in the
early 1980s.
An initial contract expected to lead to a Pounds 100m computer order for the
British Army has been awarded to a consortium led by Bull Information
Systems, UK subsidiary of Groupe Bull of France, David White writes.
Bull won the Pounds 1m trials contract against two other consortia, one led
by Hewlett-Packard and including British Telecommunications, the other
headed by the computer services company EDS-Scicon.
The Unicom system will provide the Army with an integrated computer network
for the administration of personnel, training, pay, catering, stores and
equipment.
