<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Croats advance in defiance of UN reprimand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER, REUTER and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, WASHINGTON, BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CROATIAN forces yesterday pressed forward in their drive to secure control
of strategic Serb-held territory in the republic despite a reprimand from
the United Nations Security Council.
President Franjo Tudjman of Croatia offered to withdraw his army if Serb
militia handed over heavy artillery seized from United Nations-supervised
arms depots in Croatia's four UN-monitored zones.
He said: 'We must install civilian power and normalise life in the region.
Our military forces will withdraw from the regions they have liberated in so
far as the Serb paramilitary forces are disarmed and give up the heavy
weapons they seized,' said Croatian radio.
Mr Tudjman also said Croatian police would replace all military forces in
the region, a move likely to be fiercely opposed by Serb militias who have
refused to disband under the year-old UN peace plan.
After two French peacekeepers were killed on Monday, near the Adriatic port
of Zadar, France announced it was sending a naval task force led by the
aircraft carrier Clemenceau into the Adriatic Sea.
Clashes between Serb and Croatian fighters yesterday appeared confined to
the area around the vital Maslenica bridge, which joins Croatia's heartland
with the southern Dalmatian coast.
But a UN spokesperson cited 'disturbing reports of unusual Croatian troop
movements' south of Knin, the centre of Krajina, outside the area of
conflict. With the Croatian army in control of the damaged and vital
Maslenica bridge since Monday, Serbs in Belgrade continued to sign up to
fight to defend Krajina, the self-proclaimed Serb state which stretches from
the Dalmatian hinterland to Croatia's border with Serbia.
Western diplomats fear the fighting could spread. At least 10,000 people
were killed in 1991 when Serb fighters, backed by the Yugoslav Army, took up
arms against Croatian independence.
A UN ceasefire last January froze the Serbo-Croat conflict although the
Croatian government was increasingly frustrated by Krajina's Serbs who have
virtually severed the republic.
The Security Council on Monday condemned Croatian attacks on Serb-held
territory in the UN zone and demanded that Serbs return heavy weapons to UN
supervision.
Meanwhile, Mr Vitaly Churkin, a Russian deputy foreign minister, flies to
Croatia today to urge the end of what the Moscow has described as
'irresponsible terrorist action' by Croatian fighters.
Judy Dempsey adds from Berlin: Mr Klaus Kinkel, Germany's foreign minister,
said he hoped any decision by the Security Council on whether to enforce a
no-fly zone over Bosnia-Hercegovina, would not break the ruling coalition.
But his remarks, which imply more a warning than a hope, coincided with
deepening divisions within the coalition about Germany's participation in
surveillance flights by Nato AWACS aircraft if the UN decides on
implementing the no-fly zone.
Earlier this week, Mr Manfred Worner, the Nato secretary general, warned
that any Nato operation could be undermined if German crews did not
participate.
The US, acknowledging that five oil barge groups on the Danube river appear
to be heading towards Serbia in violation of UN sanctions, said yesterday it
was up to Romania and Bulgaria to do whatever is needed to force compliance,
Reuter reports from Washington.
State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said the US and the UN sanctions
committee had told both governments they had authority under UN resolution
787 to stop suspected vessels.
</TEXT>
