<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Banking watchdog's role will cover small businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANKING ombudsman scheme is to be extended to cover complaints from
small businesses, Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, announced yesterday as
he disclosed that a survey had cleared banks of failing to pass on cuts in
base rates.
The Bank of England survey, which found that average loan margins had
'hardly changed' since June 1991 although fees had risen by 5 per cent, was
welcomed by banks but criticised by the Labour party and some small business
groups.
The Bank survey found that 61 per cent of small business loans linked to
base rates fell exactly in line with the 4.5 percentage point cut over the
period. Margins widened on 30 per cent of loans, and narrowed on 9 per cent
of them.
The chancellor has agreed with the British Bankers' Association to extend
the ombudsman scheme to cover complaints of maladministration from
incorporated business with a turnover below Pounds 1m. Banks initially
resisted this. Mr Lamont welcomed the confirmation of cuts in loan margins,
but said the extension of the scheme - which until now has covered only
personal customers and non-incorporated businesses - would provide 'an
independent view'.
Sir Nicholas Goodison, president of the BBA and chairman of TSB Group, said
the inquiry had been 'worth doing' and had laid to rest accusations against
the banks which led Mr Lamont to call for an inquiry.
Sir Nicholas said banks had been concerned that Mr Laurence Shurman, the
banking ombudsman, would be asked to adjudicate on matters of 'commercial
judgment' such as loan margins, but they were happy at the final terms of
reference.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, who said that the largest four banks
had increased charges by Pounds 1.5bn in 3 1/2 years, said the chancellor
had proved to be a 'pushover for the banking establishment'.
Mr Brown said the report offered 'no comfort at all to thousands hit by bank
charges, high margins and overcharging'.
The banking ombudsman, funded by the banks, last year received 10,109
complaints - 60 per cent up on 1991. The ombudsman's council said it hoped
for 'an early start' to the changes.
Mr Derek Wanless, chief executive of National Westminster Bank, said the
bank had strengthened its internal complaints procedure, and he did not
think the ombudsman would face a wave of complaints.
Mr Stan Mendham, of the Forum of Small Business lobby group, said the
inquiry had 'let the banks off the hook' because loan margins and fees were
less important than restrictions in credit levels and availability.
Banks welcome survey, Page 11
</TEXT>
