<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / International Capital Markets: Doubts on future of equities
study
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A SHADOW was cast yesterday over the future of Market 2000, the Securities
and Exchange Commission's potentially ground-breaking study of US equities
trading, when Mr William Heyman, the head of market regulation at the SEC
and the man in charge of the study, announced his resignation.
Mr Heyman, who joined the SEC in February 1991, said he would leave the
agency on March 18, primarily because he felt that, with a new Democratic
administration taking over the reins of government in Washington, it was
time to move on.
Mr Heyman was a prominent Republican and fund-raiser for President George
Bush.
The departure of Mr Heyman could cause problems for the Market 2000 study,
which is scheduled for publication in May or June and will include important
recommendations for updating the regulation of equities markets.
Although the SEC says that the bulk of the work on the study has been
finished, the absence of the man responsible for its completion could cause
complications.
Mr Heyman, however, believes that any delay in the release of the study will
not be caused by his departure, but by changes within the SEC, in Congress
and in the government.
He said: 'I would like to have stayed to finish Market 2000, but I concluded
that it would come behind everything else that is done here.'
</TEXT>
